==After the season==
Nebraska finished in a tie for 1st place in the Big 12 North Division and also tied for 1st conference-wide, with a final record of 11-2 (7-1). 

The events which took place at the end of the season put a strain on the system of college rankings and polls.  The Cornhuskers lost their final regular season game to {{cfb link|year=2001|school=University of Colorado at Boulder|team=Colorado Buffaloes|title=Colorado}} 36-62, leaving both tied for 1st place in the Big 12 North Division.  As Colorado won the head-to-head contest, Colorado then participated in the Big 12 Championship and defeated {{cfb link|year=2001|school=The University of Texas at Austin|team=Texas Longhorns|title=Texas}} 39-37.  Despite Colorado's accomplishments, Nebraska's strength-of-schedule component in the [[BCS|Bowl Championship Series]] selection system resulted in the Cornhuskers being selected to play in the [[2002 Rose Bowl]] for the [[BCS National Championship Game]] against [[2001 Miami Hurricanes football team|Miami]], despite the fact that Nebraska had not played in its own conference championship game and technically had not even won its own division.

Nebraska then fell to Miami 14-37 in the Rose Bowl, but the controversy of these events led to more modifications to the BCS formula, which followed a pattern of seasonal tweaks dating back nearly to when the BCS system was implemented.

Senior Cornhusker quarterback [[Eric Crouch]] was the 2001 recipient of the [[Walter Camp Award]], the [[Davey O'Brien Award]], and the [[Heisman Trophy]].  Coach Solich was also selected Big 12 Football Coach of the Year.

